WEBVTT

00:01.415 --> 00:02.450
[soft piano music plays]

00:15.291 --> 00:18.984
[people softly chattering]

00:30.237 --> 00:31.065
- Big day.

00:32.066 --> 00:33.274
- I guess so.

00:33.309 --> 00:35.207
- Seriously, you
should be very proud.

00:38.900 --> 00:39.729
- Thanks.

00:41.110 --> 00:43.077
- Time to get
started, everybody.

00:43.112 --> 00:45.217
So who's up first?

00:45.252 --> 00:48.979
[pulsing electronic music]

02:04.331 --> 02:06.367
[woman sighs]

02:06.402 --> 02:10.130
[pulsing electronic music]

02:14.858 --> 02:16.066
- [Man] Can we get this rolling?

02:16.101 --> 02:17.137
- We're almost there.

02:18.207 --> 02:20.001
- Tell me it'll work.
- It'll work.

02:22.211 --> 02:23.108
- Everything is online.

02:24.868 --> 02:26.146
- Thank you for your patience.

02:26.180 --> 02:27.388
What we're presenting here today

02:27.423 --> 02:29.149
is nothing short
of a breakthrough.

02:29.183 --> 02:30.805
I think you'll be pleased to see

02:30.840 --> 02:33.670
it aligns with your goals at
Syntec Lab, Mr. Montgomery,

02:33.705 --> 02:34.982
and, certainly, it
puts the university

02:35.016 --> 02:37.087
on the cutting-edge of
human sensory research.

02:37.122 --> 02:38.848
All right, ready to go?

02:38.882 --> 02:40.194
Everyone, this is Quinn.

02:40.229 --> 02:42.162
Quinn has been working with
us the past couple months

02:42.196 --> 02:44.888
on a project that we're
calling the Sonic Sleeves.

02:44.923 --> 02:46.511
It's relatively simple.

02:46.545 --> 02:49.169
Based, in part, on the early
work of Paul Bach-y-Rita,

02:49.203 --> 02:51.895
we're using the
mechanoreceptors in the skin

02:51.930 --> 02:55.382
to turn sounds, like my voice,

02:55.416 --> 02:57.315
into pulses that
are felt by Quinn,

02:57.349 --> 02:59.834
who, as you may have
noticed, is deaf.

02:59.869 --> 03:02.492
And these pulses cause
patterns of vibration,

03:02.527 --> 03:07.359
which help Quinn to, in
essence, hear by feeling.

03:09.741 --> 03:10.569
Are you ready?

03:11.915 --> 03:14.780
Hello.
[beeping]

03:14.815 --> 03:17.197
Hello.
[beeping]

03:17.231 --> 03:19.923
Hello.
[beeping]

03:19.958 --> 03:22.202
[soft music]

03:26.723 --> 03:29.243
- That's a little easy.

03:29.278 --> 03:31.314
Most interactions
begin that way.

03:33.143 --> 03:37.803
- Downtown, downtown.
[beeping]

03:42.429 --> 03:45.328
Downtown.
[beeping]

03:54.958 --> 03:56.236
We'll go again.

03:57.754 --> 03:59.791
Cheeseburger.
[beeping]

03:59.825 --> 04:02.207
Cheeseburger.
[beeping]

04:19.466 --> 04:22.331
Happy days.
[beeping]

04:22.365 --> 04:25.886
Happy days.
[beeping]

04:29.303 --> 04:31.443
- Let's go ahead and
stop right there.

04:32.341 --> 04:33.583
Apologies, Ted,
Diana, I was assured

04:33.618 --> 04:35.309
we had some of these
bugs worked out.

04:35.344 --> 04:37.311
- [Ted] Well, let's
hope we do next time.

04:37.346 --> 04:38.968
- If you just give us
a little bit more time.

04:39.002 --> 04:41.453
They were working
perfectly, I assure you.

04:49.496 --> 04:51.083
It's not your fault.

05:02.025 --> 05:03.372
- Was there a reason you started

05:03.406 --> 05:05.684
with a device for the deaf?

05:09.101 --> 05:12.001
Was it personal to you?

05:12.035 --> 05:13.382
- Who are you?

05:13.416 --> 05:15.176
How do you know
what I'm working on?

05:21.182 --> 05:22.494
I'm Dr. Frederick Amberger.

05:23.944 --> 05:26.084
- Should I have heard of you?
- No.

05:26.118 --> 05:29.846
My work has always been
done behind closed doors,

05:29.881 --> 05:33.505
attributed to others or
just plain forgotten.

05:35.369 --> 05:37.026
But I think you can
help change that.

05:37.060 --> 05:37.889
- Your work?

05:39.442 --> 05:43.722
- Seeking out a path to
new sensory experiences,

05:43.757 --> 05:47.105
through our sensory-enlightened
counterparts.

05:50.384 --> 05:52.352
- Sensory-enlightened?

05:52.386 --> 05:54.492
- Where others see disability,

05:54.526 --> 05:56.425
I see transformative individuals

05:56.459 --> 06:01.464
with a great aptitude for
realigning their sensory inputs.

06:02.431 --> 06:03.363
See for yourself.

06:10.956 --> 06:14.374
I believe you can
unlock the sixth sense

06:14.408 --> 06:18.412
by combining the strengths
of five individuals,

06:18.447 --> 06:21.415
each lacking one of the
five fundamental senses.

06:21.450 --> 06:23.452
Sight, hearing, taste,
touch, and smell.

06:25.557 --> 06:28.388
- Combining, how,
that's not possible.

06:29.734 --> 06:33.323
- I thought so, too,
until I witnessed it.

06:34.980 --> 06:38.743
I've witnessed many things that
would be deemed impossible.

06:39.847 --> 06:42.402
- How are you defining
the sixth sense?

06:42.436 --> 06:46.578
- As a new way to
understand, feel, visualize,

06:46.613 --> 06:48.580
and experience the
physical world around us,

06:48.615 --> 06:51.790
illuminating the entire
electromagnetic spectrum

06:51.825 --> 06:55.276
into information
that can be perceived

06:57.175 --> 06:58.590
as easily as me looking
at you right now.

06:58.625 --> 07:02.905
- Look, this sounds
interesting, but I-

07:02.939 --> 07:04.458
- You know as well as I do,

07:04.493 --> 07:07.461
the next frontier of
discovery isn't out there.

07:10.602 --> 07:11.431
It's in here.

07:14.157 --> 07:16.470
Don't let the small
failures define you.

07:20.612 --> 07:24.996
Instead, ask yourself how
far you're willing to go

07:26.376 --> 07:28.206
to find the answers you seek.

07:30.829 --> 07:32.521
I look forward to
hearing from you.

07:35.489 --> 07:39.044
[swirling electronic music]

07:55.060 --> 07:58.650
[discordant piano pounding]

08:10.110 --> 08:13.700
[swirling electronic music]

08:19.568 --> 08:23.813
- Seriously, Bob, you can't
wait until after dinner?

08:23.848 --> 08:26.057
- Well, I still have
to get through dinner.

08:26.091 --> 08:26.920
- It's fine, Mom.

08:38.241 --> 08:40.140
- Well, according to the
court order, she should be.

08:47.872 --> 08:51.289
- So, Jules, catch us up.

08:52.462 --> 08:53.533
How's school going?

08:55.465 --> 08:56.294
- It's fine.

08:59.711 --> 09:01.230
- Care to elaborate?

09:01.264 --> 09:02.714
- Good Lord, Jules,
give her something.

09:02.749 --> 09:05.475
She's had the courtesy to
invite you into our home.

09:07.408 --> 09:09.549
- So this isn't my home anymore?

09:09.583 --> 09:10.929
The house I was raised in.

09:13.414 --> 09:15.589
How long do I have to
serve out this penance for?

09:15.624 --> 09:18.143
Three years obviously
isn't enough.

09:18.178 --> 09:20.111
Four, five, the rest of my life?

09:20.145 --> 09:22.596
- You made your bed.
- All right.

09:22.631 --> 09:26.704
If you two aren't going to
bother to try, why should I?

09:26.738 --> 09:28.602
- I had a horrible day, Mom.

09:28.637 --> 09:29.845
Is that what you wanna hear?

09:32.295 --> 09:33.503
- My project failed.

09:41.615 --> 09:42.547
- [Mom] What project?

09:49.174 --> 09:52.315
- It's a sensory
device for the deaf.

09:56.561 --> 09:59.150
It's a wearable technology
that helps you hear

10:00.323 --> 10:01.359
through the vibrations
of the skin.

10:09.022 --> 10:10.610
- No.

10:10.644 --> 10:12.646
- You realize you can't
make her whole again, right?

10:12.681 --> 10:13.716
- Bob!

10:16.685 --> 10:17.617
- I'm not ready, Kath.

10:24.693 --> 10:27.557
- I'm sorry, this was a mistake.

10:29.974 --> 10:33.667
[pulsing electronic music]

10:46.507 --> 10:48.164
[sighing]

10:48.199 --> 10:51.858
[pulsing electronic music]

11:11.774 --> 11:13.017
[Jules sighs]

11:13.051 --> 11:16.779
[pulsing electronic music]

11:51.055 --> 11:53.643
[siren wails]

11:54.886 --> 11:57.682
[droning music]

12:02.894 --> 12:03.792
What's the meaning of this?

12:03.826 --> 12:04.793
- So it was personal, then.

12:06.760 --> 12:08.866
- Why do you have something
about my sister in here?

12:08.900 --> 12:09.729
- You like tea?

12:10.902 --> 12:11.731
I'll make tea.

12:23.501 --> 12:25.745
- Why are you cataloging
people's suffering?

12:28.023 --> 12:29.783
- I'm not cataloging suffering.

12:29.818 --> 12:31.889
- These people's lives
are changed forever.

12:31.923 --> 12:33.787
Dana's life has
changed completely.

12:33.822 --> 12:37.446
What shaped her, what drove
her can't be reclaimed.

12:37.480 --> 12:39.275
- Isn't that what you're trying
to do with your contraption?

12:39.310 --> 12:41.657
- It's a path
forward, hopefully.

12:41.691 --> 12:43.935
- What if there's another path?

12:43.970 --> 12:44.798
- [Jules] What, this?

12:46.558 --> 12:50.908
- On second thought, I
think breakfast is in order.

12:53.945 --> 12:57.052
The human body is made
up of layers of cells,

12:58.881 --> 13:03.161
each with receptors
that translate the
energy of a stimulus

13:03.196 --> 13:07.372
into electrical signals ending
in the somatosensory cortex.

13:09.202 --> 13:13.516
Generally, we categorize
these as our five senses.

13:15.829 --> 13:18.832
On their own, these
senses are imperfect.

13:25.356 --> 13:28.842
Imagine what it would be like
if you ate this piece of bread

13:28.877 --> 13:30.948
and it smelled like nothing.

13:30.982 --> 13:33.295
Imagine if you
touched it and it felt

13:33.329 --> 13:36.401
like a gooey, dripping liquid,

13:36.436 --> 13:39.991
devoid of shape and structure.

13:40.026 --> 13:40.854
What do you have?

13:41.751 --> 13:43.305
- A mess.

13:43.339 --> 13:45.755
- No, you'd have our breakfast.

13:47.240 --> 13:48.758
[sizzling]

13:48.793 --> 13:49.829
And when you turn on the heat.

13:53.108 --> 13:54.178
- They all come together.

13:54.212 --> 13:55.869
- Exactly.

13:55.904 --> 13:58.527
- But how, how do
they come together

13:58.561 --> 14:00.391
when we're talking about people?

14:00.425 --> 14:02.151
- Initially, a
controlled environment.

14:02.186 --> 14:04.602
Isolate the sensory enhancements

14:04.636 --> 14:06.535
for each enlightened individual,

14:06.569 --> 14:09.710
identify the pathways of
their sensory realignment.

14:11.126 --> 14:12.955
Then provide a little direction

14:14.474 --> 14:17.063
via some technological
augmentation

14:18.650 --> 14:23.655
to unlock what is already
present within them.

14:24.311 --> 14:25.934
- [Jules] Why the five?

14:25.968 --> 14:28.246
- Well, imagine an electrical
current when it's overloaded.

14:28.281 --> 14:30.939
The five together
help balance the load.

14:32.112 --> 14:34.080
Eventually, we'll
move beyond this need,

14:35.391 --> 14:36.461
but it's where we start.

14:36.496 --> 14:37.946
- But that's impossible.

14:37.980 --> 14:40.258
What you're proposing,
there's no precedent.

14:40.293 --> 14:42.019
- We have to strike
that word "impossible"

14:42.053 --> 14:43.227
from your vocabulary.

14:44.849 --> 14:48.094
The work in that notebook
contains precedent.

14:49.405 --> 14:50.820
We just have to go further.

14:53.099 --> 14:54.376
- But why we?

14:54.410 --> 14:55.549
I don't know what
I bring to this.

14:57.068 --> 15:00.451
- A curious mind, a penchant
for discovery, longevity.

15:04.489 --> 15:06.077
While you may not be
able to articulate it,

15:06.112 --> 15:09.046
you, too, see the
transcendent nature

15:09.080 --> 15:11.772
of our sensory-enlightened
counterparts.

15:12.981 --> 15:16.260
I need someone like you to help
me carry this work forward.

15:17.640 --> 15:19.435
- Who are you, really?

15:21.127 --> 15:26.028
[eerie music]
[whispering]

15:40.456 --> 15:44.219
[shimmering electronic music]

16:29.712 --> 16:30.990
- You want tea?

16:33.578 --> 16:34.786
I'll make tea.

16:37.858 --> 16:39.032
- We already have tea.

16:40.068 --> 16:42.001
[knocking]

16:42.035 --> 16:43.036
- Dad?

16:45.280 --> 16:46.143
How come you're not dressed?

16:46.177 --> 16:47.765
We have an appointment.

16:47.799 --> 16:48.628
Hi?

16:50.112 --> 16:53.012
Dad, it's a little late to
be getting help around here.

16:53.046 --> 16:53.840
We're way past that.

16:53.874 --> 16:55.083
- I'm not help.

16:55.117 --> 16:56.187
- She's a colleague.

16:58.534 --> 17:00.364
- [sighs] Not this again.

17:05.196 --> 17:06.094
College student?

17:06.887 --> 17:07.716
- [Jules] Yeah.

17:08.648 --> 17:10.960
- Well, my apologies.

17:10.995 --> 17:12.100
My father, I'm afraid to say,

17:12.134 --> 17:14.067
is not his best self these days.

17:14.102 --> 17:15.586
And we have an appointment.

17:15.620 --> 17:17.588
- My son has little imagination.

17:18.658 --> 17:20.418
He knows not of what he speaks.

17:20.453 --> 17:22.075
- And it's time for you to go.

17:23.318 --> 17:25.734
[shimmering electronic music]

17:25.768 --> 17:29.772
- You've got roughly
a quadrillion synapses
in your brain,

17:29.807 --> 17:32.603
a quadrillion connections
between nerves,

17:32.637 --> 17:35.640
all happening right now,
carving out the pathways

17:35.675 --> 17:37.194
that make us who we are.

17:37.228 --> 17:39.127
To give you a
little perspective,

17:39.161 --> 17:41.232
the number of stars
in the Milky Way

17:41.267 --> 17:43.200
is about 300 billion.

17:43.234 --> 17:45.236
So you've got 1000
times more synapses

17:45.271 --> 17:48.895
happening inside your
brain than all the stars

17:48.929 --> 17:50.828
in the Milky Way galaxy.

17:50.862 --> 17:52.105
- [Frederick Voiceover] We
have to strike that word

17:52.140 --> 17:53.072
"impossible" from
your vocabulary.

17:54.694 --> 17:57.041
The work in that notebook
contains precedent.

17:58.318 --> 18:00.803
We just have to go further.
- Doing all this computational

18:00.838 --> 18:03.116
work, well, that's
what we're here for.

18:03.151 --> 18:07.189
[shimmering electronic music]

18:20.858 --> 18:22.894
- Day one, October 12th, 1985.

18:24.137 --> 18:25.621
Now what's your name, young man?

18:25.656 --> 18:28.003
- [Young Man] Anthony.
- Anthony.

18:28.037 --> 18:30.109
We've invited several potential
candidates in for interview.

18:31.144 --> 18:32.318
- Why are you doing it?

18:32.352 --> 18:35.597
- A way to better
understand our senses.

18:35.631 --> 18:37.840
It's our belief that
those deemed disabled

18:37.875 --> 18:41.258
by our society hold the
key to understanding

18:41.292 --> 18:44.157
how the brain rewires
itself in the face

18:44.192 --> 18:47.678
of faulty, damaged, or
missing sensory inputs.

18:47.712 --> 18:49.852
- Oh, that's easy.

18:49.887 --> 18:50.922
Smell with your nose,

18:52.165 --> 18:53.994
touch with your
fingers and toes,

18:55.306 --> 18:56.687
taste with your tongue,

18:56.721 --> 18:57.929
hear with your ears,

18:59.414 --> 19:01.312
and see with your eyes.

19:02.762 --> 19:06.179
- You need Missy
to tell you that?

19:06.214 --> 19:08.492
[shimmering electronic music]

19:08.526 --> 19:09.838
- [Frederick Voiceover] Day 23.

19:09.872 --> 19:11.080
We've selected our
initial candidates

19:11.115 --> 19:12.910
for phase one of the study.

19:12.944 --> 19:14.981
At H's prompting,
these candidates

19:15.015 --> 19:17.915
represent the loss of
the primary five senses,

19:17.949 --> 19:21.298
taste, touch, smell,
hearing, and sight.

19:21.332 --> 19:25.129
[shimmering electronic music]

19:35.553 --> 19:36.658
Day 98.

19:36.692 --> 19:38.177
Breakthrough.

19:38.211 --> 19:41.318
Testing Subject Three,
representing loss of sight.

19:41.352 --> 19:43.251
- 15.
- We detect enhanced

19:43.285 --> 19:46.909
hearing capabilities, as well
as an advanced olfactory.

19:46.944 --> 19:48.428
- Seven o'clock.

19:48.463 --> 19:50.085
- [Frederick Voiceover] Day 132.

19:50.119 --> 19:54.020
At this point, we've detected
a myriad of enhanced senses

19:54.054 --> 19:56.712
to varying degrees
in all our subjects,

19:56.747 --> 19:59.336
with consistent results
against our control group.

19:59.370 --> 20:02.270
H has suggested placing our
subjects in a group setting

20:02.304 --> 20:04.237
to study the effects
of social interaction

20:04.272 --> 20:08.379
on sensory input, the
human factor, if you will.

20:08.414 --> 20:10.726
[shimmering electronic music]

20:10.761 --> 20:12.349
Day 172.

20:12.383 --> 20:14.213
After noting interesting effects

20:14.247 --> 20:16.767
based on social
interaction, we've decided

20:16.801 --> 20:19.701
to test if we can,
essentially, link

20:19.735 --> 20:22.531
our subjects'
sensory experiences.

20:22.566 --> 20:24.533
We shall attempt this
through restricting

20:24.568 --> 20:27.605
our subjects' usable
sensory inputs,

20:27.640 --> 20:31.402
monitoring their brain activity
via one set of sensors,

20:31.437 --> 20:33.956
while creating a shared feed

20:33.991 --> 20:37.063
of their combined
electromagnetic brainwaves.

20:37.097 --> 20:40.860
[shimmering electronic music]

20:51.836 --> 20:54.287
- Can anybody else see this?

20:54.322 --> 20:56.393
[shimmering electronic music]

20:56.427 --> 20:57.773
- It's incredible.

21:02.364 --> 21:04.573
- How am I seeing this?

21:04.608 --> 21:07.404
This is rad!

21:07.438 --> 21:09.854
- What are they
seeing, experiencing?

21:09.889 --> 21:13.686
[shimmering electronic music]

21:38.400 --> 21:39.884
- [Man] This is nuts.

21:39.919 --> 21:41.334
- Amberger's onto something
truly game-changing,

21:41.369 --> 21:42.784
evolution and advancement
to understanding

21:42.818 --> 21:44.130
of the human brain.

21:44.164 --> 21:44.993
Game-changing.

21:46.408 --> 21:48.617
- [Woman] Don't do this, Jules.

21:48.652 --> 21:50.239
- Do what?

21:50.274 --> 21:51.655
- [Man] Lose focus.

21:51.689 --> 21:53.346
We're getting one more
chance with the sleeves,

21:53.381 --> 21:55.244
and that's where
our head should be.

21:55.279 --> 21:56.349
- [Woman] He's right.

21:56.384 --> 21:58.834
- Skip to one file, and
then read it on the way.

21:58.869 --> 22:00.111
- [Man] On the way where?

22:01.009 --> 22:01.837
- Breakfast.

22:03.183 --> 22:05.082
[pulsing electronic music]

22:05.116 --> 22:07.084
- I don't understand,
what did they see?

22:09.673 --> 22:12.227
- I think they
somehow experienced

22:12.261 --> 22:14.436
the entire
electromagnetic spectrum,

22:16.265 --> 22:18.854
allowing them to feel the energy

22:18.889 --> 22:21.512
of the world surrounding
them, including each other.

22:23.411 --> 22:25.067
- That sounds terrible.

22:25.102 --> 22:25.930
You wouldn't want to
sense that much noise.

22:25.965 --> 22:26.862
- Exactly.

22:33.386 --> 22:35.319
- How long have you
not been able to taste?

22:37.632 --> 22:38.460
Can you smell?

22:39.703 --> 22:41.360
- Yeah, I can still smell.

22:41.394 --> 22:43.396
- Every tested your
acuity for smell?

22:45.329 --> 22:46.434
- Just because I can't
taste doesn't mean

22:46.468 --> 22:48.539
I've somehow got a
world class nose.

22:49.575 --> 22:51.300
- Just curious.

22:51.335 --> 22:52.543
What about you?

22:54.234 --> 22:55.546
- What about me?

22:55.581 --> 22:58.894
- Do you think that
you're more or less

22:58.929 --> 23:01.690
aware of your surroundings now?

23:01.725 --> 23:04.555
- This requires me to be more
aware of my surroundings.

23:04.590 --> 23:07.351
- [Amberger] And would you say
that, because of the chair,

23:08.352 --> 23:10.147
you feel space differently now?

23:12.805 --> 23:14.427
- I guess.

23:14.462 --> 23:15.911
- [Amberger] And would you
say that the loss of taste

23:15.946 --> 23:19.536
has shifted how you
approach your daily life?

23:19.570 --> 23:21.400
- That goes without saying.

23:21.434 --> 23:22.642
- Currently, we
have limited control

23:22.677 --> 23:25.714
over our brain's
ability to rewire

23:25.749 --> 23:29.477
and realign sensory
inputs, but I believe

23:29.511 --> 23:33.446
that with your help,
we can finish the work

23:33.481 --> 23:34.620
I started in here.

23:36.173 --> 23:40.591
Unlock the code to guiding
these sensory pathways

23:41.523 --> 23:43.560
and we're on our
way to expanding

23:43.594 --> 23:45.596
the human sensory experience.

23:45.631 --> 23:47.149
- I'm perfectly fine how I am.

23:47.184 --> 23:50.808
- You're more than fine,
you're enlightened.

23:50.843 --> 23:52.465
- I'm sorry, I
can't help but feel

23:52.500 --> 23:54.985
like this is a little beyond
what's actually possible.

23:55.019 --> 23:56.987
Sure, we had a little
hiccough with the sleeves,

23:57.021 --> 23:59.023
but we can figure that out.

23:59.058 --> 24:00.611
It's tangible, real.

24:01.819 --> 24:03.545
- And something that
not too long ago

24:04.650 --> 24:05.478
was thought to be impossible.

24:07.860 --> 24:12.243
- Without thinking, what
do you smell right now?

24:14.522 --> 24:15.350
- Bubblegum.

24:20.666 --> 24:24.014
â™ª Is this just a dream

24:24.048 --> 24:27.949
â™ª Or is this the real thing

24:27.983 --> 24:30.261
- You both know why I
started down this path.

24:31.539 --> 24:34.990
You both know I can't do
any of this without you.

24:40.444 --> 24:42.826
- So what exactly are we
talking about doing here?

24:45.829 --> 24:49.004
- First, we all need to get
up to speed on Amberger's work

24:49.039 --> 24:52.421
and seek out any supporting
data we can find.

24:52.456 --> 24:55.908
[pulsing electronic music]

25:03.536 --> 25:05.538
Then we compile, blending
Amberger's research

25:05.573 --> 25:07.885
with our current track
into a possible thesis.

25:09.231 --> 25:11.510
When we feel we've nailed it,

25:11.544 --> 25:14.029
I'll go have a conversation
with Professor Johnston.

25:15.790 --> 25:17.585
- [Professor] Hard no.

25:17.619 --> 25:18.655
- You didn't even read it.

25:18.689 --> 25:19.897
- I skimmed enough.

25:19.932 --> 25:22.106
Creating new sensory inputs,

25:22.141 --> 25:24.039
feeling the world around us.

25:24.074 --> 25:26.352
This is a little
touchy-feely New Agey

25:26.386 --> 25:28.078
for a science lab,
don't you think?

25:29.631 --> 25:31.046
It has "enlightened" in
the title, for hell's sake,

25:31.081 --> 25:35.119
and who in the world is
this Dr. Amberger character?

25:35.154 --> 25:37.121
Actually, don't care.

25:37.156 --> 25:39.572
The reality is we
are about to lose

25:39.607 --> 25:41.574
a large chunk of funding
because the experiment

25:41.609 --> 25:45.129
you assured me was ready for
prime time obviously wasn't.

25:47.304 --> 25:49.686
You have a chance to fix this,

25:49.720 --> 25:51.791
and that's exactly
what you're gonna do.

25:51.826 --> 25:56.555
This is you simply
spinning your wheels

25:56.589 --> 25:59.109
after experiencing a
little bit of failure.

26:00.351 --> 26:03.700
Get focused and make
those sleeves work.

26:03.734 --> 26:07.186
[pulsing electronic music]

26:08.946 --> 26:09.775
- So?

26:13.295 --> 26:15.159
- We're a go.
- Seriously?

26:15.194 --> 26:18.473
- We'll have to move forward
the sleeves, but, yeah.

26:18.507 --> 26:19.957
Let's do this.

26:19.992 --> 26:20.855
- So what's the plan?

26:22.373 --> 26:23.443
- We need subjects.

26:26.688 --> 26:28.103
- I posted on every
local disability group

26:28.138 --> 26:30.105
I could find online,
and I'm already getting

26:30.140 --> 26:31.590
some positive responses.

26:31.624 --> 26:33.074
- Great.

26:33.108 --> 26:34.731
I'll drive these by the
school for the deaf and blind.

26:34.765 --> 26:36.180
Sam's taking the health clubs.

26:36.215 --> 26:37.665
Maybe post some at coffee shops

26:37.699 --> 26:39.149
and stuff like that, too?

26:39.183 --> 26:40.806
- Yeah, is he okay?

26:42.014 --> 26:43.912
- What do you mean?

26:43.947 --> 26:44.810
- Something's off.

26:46.535 --> 26:48.192
- He disappears sometimes.

26:52.403 --> 26:54.509
- Let's just concentrate
on getting these out.

26:54.543 --> 26:55.441
- Okay.

26:55.475 --> 26:58.893
[pulsing electronic music]

27:20.604 --> 27:22.330
- I think you should
ask your sister

27:22.364 --> 27:23.642
to come join the study.

27:23.676 --> 27:28.647
- She, well, my family
isn't that really fond of me

27:29.406 --> 27:30.234
at this point.

27:37.828 --> 27:39.658
- Family's difficult
to navigate at times.

27:44.870 --> 27:45.733
- Does your son know?

27:45.767 --> 27:47.079
What we're doing. I mean.

27:48.874 --> 27:50.669
- Family's difficult
to navigate.

27:54.224 --> 27:55.846
- I mean, he seemed concerned.

27:57.883 --> 28:00.644
Is everything okay?

28:04.061 --> 28:06.374
- Our time on this
planet is short,

28:07.858 --> 28:11.206
and mine, perhaps
a bit shorter now.

28:20.733 --> 28:22.942
Thanks for giving
me a second chance.

28:22.977 --> 28:25.082
- [Jules] See you tomorrow.

28:25.117 --> 28:25.945
- Tomorrow.

28:35.058 --> 28:37.681
[Jules sighs]

28:39.787 --> 28:41.409
[Amberger gasps]

28:41.443 --> 28:45.931
[rolling, tinkling
electronic music]

29:23.865 --> 29:25.349
- You wanna try it?

29:27.835 --> 29:29.733
Sir, sir?

29:30.838 --> 29:31.873
Are you okay?

29:34.186 --> 29:35.981
I've been sleepwalking.

29:37.845 --> 29:39.191
Sir, sir?

29:40.502 --> 29:41.987
You gotta wake up, man.

29:44.196 --> 29:45.024
Oh, damn.

29:48.648 --> 29:51.548
- I have no ID here.

29:52.721 --> 29:53.964
- Sir, can you
tell me your name?

29:57.381 --> 29:58.658
- What is this?

29:58.693 --> 30:00.315
- Sir, we think you
were sleepwalking.

30:00.350 --> 30:03.077
Can you tell me your
name, where you live?

30:05.389 --> 30:06.977
- I'm meeting Jules.

30:07.012 --> 30:07.875
- Who's Jules?

30:09.014 --> 30:11.568
- She's helping me
with my experiments.

30:12.880 --> 30:13.984
- Experiments?

30:14.882 --> 30:17.332
Do you know where
you were meeting her?

30:17.367 --> 30:20.853
[haunting ambient music]

30:23.994 --> 30:25.340
- I don't remember.

30:25.375 --> 30:26.514
- [Cop] Whoa, whoa.

30:26.548 --> 30:28.171
What is your name, sir?

30:32.865 --> 30:34.004
- I don't know.

30:35.040 --> 30:36.904
- [Cop] It's okay, it'll come.

30:38.595 --> 30:40.045
Why don't you take
a ride with us?

30:43.738 --> 30:44.843
- Where are we going?

30:44.877 --> 30:46.914
- Somewhere we can get
you all sorted out.

30:49.537 --> 30:50.365
Take a seat.

31:03.033 --> 31:04.863
- I think we should
just get started.

31:04.897 --> 31:06.071
- He'll be here, I promise.

31:06.105 --> 31:07.727
Let's just give it a minute.

31:07.762 --> 31:10.592
- Not a great way to start
the grand experiment, Jules.

31:10.627 --> 31:13.630
[people chattering]

31:17.634 --> 31:19.222
- Jules, a word.

31:20.982 --> 31:25.435
Jules, the sensory lab is for
legitimate, scientific study,

31:25.469 --> 31:27.471
preferably the type of
study that's going to bring

31:27.506 --> 31:29.922
research funding
into the university.

31:29.957 --> 31:33.029
And I finally read this.

31:33.063 --> 31:35.065
I can say with
complete confidence

31:35.100 --> 31:38.379
that this is nonsense, the
stuff of science fiction.

31:38.413 --> 31:40.899
- Professor, with
all due respect,

31:40.933 --> 31:43.487
we know that what we perceive
with the human senses

31:43.522 --> 31:46.145
is just a fraction of
what's occurring around us,

31:46.180 --> 31:48.907
and we also know that
we can rewire the brain.

31:48.941 --> 31:51.047
If we can figure out how
to guide that rewiring,

31:51.081 --> 31:53.083
we unlock limitless
sensory potential.

31:53.118 --> 31:54.774
- You're square pegging it.

31:54.809 --> 31:57.467
Rewiring the brain is one
thing, but this sixth sense,

31:57.501 --> 32:01.057
seeing beyond what is seeable
mumbo jumbo is lunacy.

32:01.091 --> 32:02.575
- We don't see with our eyes.

32:02.610 --> 32:03.680
We don't hear with our ears.

32:03.714 --> 32:04.923
We don't taste with our tongue.

32:04.957 --> 32:06.821
It's all done in the brain.

32:06.855 --> 32:08.996
And since that's
true, it's possible,

32:09.030 --> 32:11.653
truly possible, that, with
the right sensory input,

32:11.688 --> 32:13.103
that-
- Stop!

32:13.138 --> 32:15.485
Okay, please, just stop.

32:17.314 --> 32:19.109
No more soliciting subjects,

32:19.144 --> 32:23.010
no more of this so-called
doctor of yours,

32:23.044 --> 32:26.116
and no more of this movie
of the week gobbledygook.

32:26.151 --> 32:28.118
You have a directive already.

32:28.153 --> 32:30.672
Stick to it or I'm
banning you from the lab

32:30.707 --> 32:33.054
and turning your project
over to another team.

32:36.506 --> 32:37.990
- What the hell, Jules?

32:38.025 --> 32:38.957
- What?

32:38.991 --> 32:40.337
- You lied to us.

32:40.372 --> 32:43.030
- Now he's threatening
to take our project away.

32:43.064 --> 32:43.962
Why would you do this?

32:44.997 --> 32:48.897
- Because it won't fix her.

32:48.932 --> 32:50.451
- The sleeves?

32:50.485 --> 32:51.900
Of course it won't fix her.

32:53.074 --> 32:54.489
That's not the point.

32:54.524 --> 32:57.113
- [Student] You realize your
sister's still here, right?

32:57.147 --> 32:57.976
- Of course I do.

32:59.253 --> 33:02.359
- Maybe instead of avoiding
her on your quest to fix her,

33:02.394 --> 33:04.741
you could actually try
to be part of her life.

33:04.775 --> 33:06.191
I'm sure she'd
appreciate being seen

33:06.225 --> 33:09.988
as more than a reminder
of your stupid mistake.

33:10.022 --> 33:13.163
[soft electronic music]

33:19.204 --> 33:20.067
- I gotta go.

33:20.101 --> 33:23.553
[soft electronic music]

33:44.643 --> 33:45.471
- No.

33:47.128 --> 33:48.612
No.

33:48.647 --> 33:50.545
I don't wanna see you.

33:52.823 --> 33:53.652
Don't you understand?

33:55.826 --> 34:00.831
I have so little time,
and I have to finish.

34:06.078 --> 34:08.253
- You just need to
get all the pieces.

34:12.084 --> 34:13.982
And then you can come home.

34:14.017 --> 34:17.158
[soft electronic music]

34:49.708 --> 34:52.193
[phone chimes]

34:58.199 --> 34:59.269
- Hello?

35:00.374 --> 35:01.202
Yes, this is she.

35:04.205 --> 35:05.275
Mister who?

35:08.140 --> 35:09.141
Oh.

35:10.729 --> 35:11.902
Oh, yes.

35:14.284 --> 35:15.285
Is everything okay?

35:18.978 --> 35:20.290
I'm sorry that I lied to you.

35:24.984 --> 35:26.641
And I know you're
both really mad at me,

35:26.676 --> 35:29.092
and I screwed up,

35:31.301 --> 35:33.510
and that you both
probably think I'm crazy,

35:37.204 --> 35:38.688
but they found Amberger,

35:41.553 --> 35:43.106
and I really want your help.

35:45.212 --> 35:46.074
- Who's they?

35:49.699 --> 35:51.252
- [Cop] You ever make
it over to Idaho?

35:52.357 --> 35:53.220
- Oh, hey.

35:54.738 --> 35:56.637
- Boise PD ran some prints.

35:56.671 --> 35:58.259
- I lost the biggest
fish of my life in Idaho.

35:59.536 --> 36:01.676
Fought that thing
for nearly an hour.

36:01.711 --> 36:03.264
Then it just slipped the line.

36:05.093 --> 36:06.336
Nicknamed him Goliath.

36:09.028 --> 36:10.478
Anyway, what have you got?

36:10.513 --> 36:12.791
- [Cop] Boise PD ran some
prints for an old case.

36:14.241 --> 36:15.690
- Heinrich Kline.
- Yeah.

36:15.725 --> 36:17.727
Apparently, he was developing
some top secret tech

36:17.761 --> 36:19.694
and then decided he
wanted to keep it.

36:23.284 --> 36:25.217
- I can't imagine 30-year-old
technology's worth a damn now.

36:25.252 --> 36:27.875
- Well, Uncle Sam seems to
think it's worth a trip.

36:27.909 --> 36:29.566
- Fishing alone is worth a trip.

36:29.601 --> 36:31.361
Have you alerted Boise PD?

36:31.396 --> 36:32.776
- Yeah.

36:32.811 --> 36:34.122
They're making the
call right now.

36:34.157 --> 36:35.745
- [Cop] Lucky we
found your number
stuffed inside his pocket.

36:35.779 --> 36:37.333
- Well, is he okay now?

36:37.367 --> 36:38.334
- He seems to have his
head screwed on straight,

36:38.368 --> 36:39.921
for now at least.

36:39.956 --> 36:41.129
- Jules.
- Doc!

36:41.164 --> 36:42.061
What happened, are you okay?

36:42.096 --> 36:43.235
- Yeah, I'm much better now.

36:43.270 --> 36:45.755
- This is Officer Sternes.

36:45.789 --> 36:47.205
- We better jump on
this one right away.

36:47.239 --> 36:49.207
- Are we talking about
the fishing or the case?

36:49.241 --> 36:50.242
- Exactly.

36:56.973 --> 36:57.836
- Who's Mr. Kline?

37:05.326 --> 37:07.017
Why have you been lying to us?

37:08.433 --> 37:11.056
- I assure you, everything
I shared with you

37:11.090 --> 37:13.541
is real and possible.

37:13.576 --> 37:15.129
- He's wanted by the FBI.

37:15.163 --> 37:16.993
- He's what?
- He's what?

37:21.308 --> 37:23.068
Why?

37:23.102 --> 37:24.311
- Stealing government property.

37:24.345 --> 37:26.416
- I didn't steal anything.

37:29.592 --> 37:31.283
I simply kept my research.

37:31.318 --> 37:32.422
- We'll keep him here.

37:34.113 --> 37:37.185
FBI, they want us to hold
that Kline character.

37:39.015 --> 37:40.465
- That might be a
bit of a problem.

37:43.122 --> 37:44.779
- I've put a lot
of faith in you.

37:45.780 --> 37:47.023
This means a lot more to me

37:47.057 --> 37:48.818
than I think that
you understand,

37:48.852 --> 37:51.786
so, please, tell us
what is going on.

37:57.067 --> 37:59.346
- Smell with your nose,

37:59.380 --> 38:01.348
touch with your fingers
[speaker drowned out].

38:01.382 --> 38:02.763
- [Amberger Voiceover]
Her name was Hilda.

38:02.797 --> 38:07.354
She was my whole world,
my partner in everything.

38:08.251 --> 38:09.079
- See with your eyes.

38:10.253 --> 38:12.842
- You need Missy
to tell you that?

38:14.361 --> 38:15.327
- [Amberger Voiceover] She's
the one who helped guide

38:15.362 --> 38:17.536
out experiments to
their initial success.

38:17.571 --> 38:21.368
[shimmering electronic music]

38:24.578 --> 38:25.924
It started slowly.

38:27.374 --> 38:29.686
Her muscles would
give out suddenly

38:31.170 --> 38:33.621
or she'd be stricken
with episodes of fatigue.

38:33.656 --> 38:36.383
Before we could get a handle
on what was happening,

38:36.417 --> 38:37.901
it accelerated.

38:39.834 --> 38:42.389
Hilda insisted on
continuing the work.

38:44.011 --> 38:46.496
She was convinced the Five
held the key to her cure.

38:48.671 --> 38:51.294
- Does anybody else see this?

38:53.365 --> 38:54.642
- It's incredible.

38:54.677 --> 38:56.368
- Just as we had our
first breakthrough,

38:56.403 --> 38:58.336
we faced being shut down.

38:58.370 --> 39:01.097
What are they
seeing, experiencing?

39:01.131 --> 39:04.928
[shimmering electronic music]

39:06.930 --> 39:10.417
Our higher-ups wanted
actionable, usable technology.

39:11.556 --> 39:13.523
I tried to buy some time

39:13.558 --> 39:15.525
with another project
we had developed.

39:17.562 --> 39:19.598
We called it the Sonar Suit,

39:19.633 --> 39:22.670
based on bats' use
of echolocation,

39:22.705 --> 39:26.191
sonar data translated
to electronic pulse

39:26.225 --> 39:28.952
to provide a 360 degree
view that subjects

39:28.987 --> 39:31.369
would see all at once.

39:32.542 --> 39:37.305
[shimmering electronic music]
[beeping]

39:48.558 --> 39:50.388
[gun bangs]

39:50.422 --> 39:55.393
[shimmering electronic music]
[beeping]

39:58.775 --> 40:00.950
[gun bangs]

40:00.984 --> 40:04.574
The problem was, initial
tests were so successful,

40:04.609 --> 40:08.475
it caused them to abandon
our other sensory research

40:08.509 --> 40:10.408
to concentrate
solely on the suit.

40:12.755 --> 40:14.998
So, before all of our
work with the Five

40:15.033 --> 40:18.795
was to be filed away
in some cavernous void,

40:18.830 --> 40:23.421
and the Sonar Suit sent
off to war, I liberated it.

40:23.455 --> 40:25.526
One of the original Five, Toby,

40:26.769 --> 40:30.428
had a quiet place,
far from prying eyes,

40:30.462 --> 40:31.946
which he offered
up as a safe haven

40:31.981 --> 40:33.189
to continue the work.

40:34.535 --> 40:39.126
So we left and began
living as the Ambergers.

40:39.160 --> 40:42.025
There, Hilda helped us
reconfigure the Sonar Suit

40:42.060 --> 40:44.511
into a device that
we hoped would mimic

40:44.545 --> 40:46.582
the experience of the Five.

40:46.616 --> 40:50.206
- So Hilda's H in the notebook.

40:50.240 --> 40:51.656
- [Amberger] Yes.

40:51.690 --> 40:52.519
- [Sam] What happened to her?

41:03.426 --> 41:04.496
- I don't like this.

41:04.531 --> 41:05.670
I don't think we're ready.

41:05.704 --> 41:08.017
- We've reversed the
polarity of the sensors.

41:08.051 --> 41:10.364
We've tested all of
our modifications.

41:10.398 --> 41:14.610
- Yeah, but doing this out
here, it's too dangerous.

41:14.644 --> 41:18.061
- You and I both know this
is the only viable option,

41:18.096 --> 41:21.548
free of electrical
interference, radio waves.

41:21.582 --> 41:23.032
- We could've gone into
the middle of a field.

41:23.066 --> 41:25.690
- Sure, but it wouldn't
have been as romantic.

41:27.554 --> 41:28.658
- Fine...

41:29.521 --> 41:30.833
- But, I am pulling the plug...

41:32.041 --> 41:33.594
- if anything looks
like it's going wrong.

41:37.702 --> 41:39.255
Just kiss me.

41:39.289 --> 41:41.671
[quiet music]

41:57.756 --> 41:58.723
Help me get this on.

42:13.634 --> 42:15.256
Here's to discovery.

42:19.329 --> 42:20.607
- Are you sure?

42:20.641 --> 42:21.711
- Never more.

42:29.650 --> 42:30.720
[clicking]

42:30.755 --> 42:33.378
[buzzing]

42:33.412 --> 42:34.724
Tingles.

42:34.759 --> 42:36.968
[buzzing]

42:42.352 --> 42:43.837
- [Amberger] What are you doing?

42:44.838 --> 42:46.356
- It's beautiful.

42:49.739 --> 42:51.120
- Hilda, sit down.

42:53.640 --> 42:55.607
- All those things they saw.

42:55.642 --> 42:56.470
- Sit down!

42:58.645 --> 42:59.611
- The full spectrum.

42:59.646 --> 43:00.681
- Hilda, sit!

43:04.098 --> 43:04.927
Hilda.

43:04.961 --> 43:07.170
[buzzing]

43:10.208 --> 43:11.036
Hilda.

43:12.003 --> 43:13.280
Hilda!

43:13.314 --> 43:14.143
Hilda!

43:16.386 --> 43:17.215
She passed away.

43:20.528 --> 43:21.668
- Is that why you stopped?

43:29.710 --> 43:32.610
- That, and I didn't
have all the pieces.

43:33.990 --> 43:35.371
Hilda was gone.

43:36.786 --> 43:37.891
I had a son to raise.

43:41.688 --> 43:42.620
I had to make a choice.

43:44.242 --> 43:46.624
[quiet music]

43:53.976 --> 43:55.909
- You think someone
will be coming now?

43:58.049 --> 43:59.119
- [Amberger] The
government tends to have

43:59.153 --> 44:00.396
a very long memory.

44:02.812 --> 44:04.365
- How do we finish then?

44:04.400 --> 44:07.817
- Jules, you can't be
suggesting we continue this.

44:08.853 --> 44:09.819
- I want to see it through, Max.

44:09.854 --> 44:11.856
- But the man's a fugitive.

44:20.071 --> 44:21.693
- You two have shown
me time and again

44:21.728 --> 44:23.350
your remarkable resilience,

44:23.384 --> 44:26.560
meeting all the challenges
that life throws at you,

44:26.594 --> 44:29.977
and, Max, you're right,
I need to stop seeing

44:30.012 --> 44:31.599
Dana through the
lens of my own guilt

44:31.634 --> 44:34.741
and start seeing the same
thing I see in both of you,

44:34.775 --> 44:37.191
the thing that Dr. Amberger
has finally given me

44:37.226 --> 44:40.263
the language for,
sensory enlightenment.

44:41.782 --> 44:43.577
We all know there's
something to all this,

44:43.611 --> 44:44.854
something worth exploring.

44:44.889 --> 44:46.753
- Still, Jules, we
don't have subjects,

44:46.787 --> 44:49.410
we don't have a lab, equipment.

44:49.445 --> 44:50.998
The government may be after him.

44:51.033 --> 44:53.069
- What if you two
are the subjects?

44:53.104 --> 44:54.761
That only leaves three more.

44:54.795 --> 44:58.523
- Only two more, if we
return to the quiet place,

44:58.557 --> 45:00.698
and the equipment is there.

45:00.732 --> 45:01.975
- I don't know, Jules.

45:02.872 --> 45:04.771
This is crazy.

45:04.805 --> 45:08.291
[pulsing electronic music]

45:11.778 --> 45:14.263
- Sometimes you
have to ask yourself

45:14.297 --> 45:17.922
how far you're willing to go
to find the answers you seek.

45:19.682 --> 45:21.891
The next frontier
isn't out there,

45:23.306 --> 45:24.135
it's in here.

45:25.343 --> 45:28.829
[pulsing electronic music]

45:33.247 --> 45:36.492
- No matter what, we agree
to finish the sleeves.

45:37.665 --> 45:38.770
- Of course.

45:38.805 --> 45:41.877
Sam, how about it?

45:41.911 --> 45:43.533
Are we all in for discovery?

45:44.362 --> 45:47.848
[pulsing electronic music]

45:51.818 --> 45:55.718
- If the paper gets
authored, we get top billing,

45:57.099 --> 45:58.928
since we're the
enlightened ones.

46:00.619 --> 46:01.448
- Obviously.

46:06.694 --> 46:11.078
- So, the local PD accidentally
released our Mr. Kline.

46:11.113 --> 46:12.355
Apparently, he left
with a young woman

46:12.390 --> 46:13.805
named Jules Christopher.

46:13.840 --> 46:15.600
I guess she's a
university student

46:15.634 --> 46:17.913
working something they
call a sensory lab,

46:17.947 --> 46:20.950
which, based on Kline's
file, is right up his alley.

46:20.985 --> 46:22.262
I'd say that's our first stop.

46:22.296 --> 46:23.125
Hey.

46:24.057 --> 46:25.817
- Oh, great work.

46:25.852 --> 46:27.819
Hey, there's a local
fly shop nearby.

46:27.854 --> 46:29.717
What do we say we hit
that along the way?

46:29.752 --> 46:32.928
This way, if we get stuck
in some cross-country chase,

46:32.962 --> 46:34.170
I have my license.

46:34.205 --> 46:35.862
- I can't tell if
you're joking or not.

46:36.966 --> 46:37.898
- I never joke about fishing.

46:40.901 --> 46:42.489
- If we leave now, we can
be there before nightfall,

46:42.523 --> 46:45.043
and I'm sure we can find some
other subjects on the way.

46:45.078 --> 46:46.424
- Be where by nightfall?

46:52.154 --> 46:53.362
And where have you been?

46:55.364 --> 46:57.228
I thought I warned
you about this one.

46:59.989 --> 47:01.404
You missed our appointment.

47:02.889 --> 47:05.132
I've been all over
town looking for you,

47:05.167 --> 47:07.859
and then I find you in the
company of your colleague,

47:07.894 --> 47:09.343
planning an escape somewhere?

47:12.036 --> 47:13.382
- It's none of your concern.

47:13.416 --> 47:15.349
- Dad, you are my concern.

47:15.384 --> 47:16.868
That's why we're
making this move,

47:16.903 --> 47:18.387
so you can get the
medical attention you need

47:18.421 --> 47:19.940
and be cared for properly.

47:21.597 --> 47:23.875
- I am much too busy
for that nonsense.

47:23.910 --> 47:25.635
- This isn't a negotiation.

47:27.016 --> 47:28.362
Dad, stop!

47:32.919 --> 47:34.610
If only you could
put that big brain

47:34.644 --> 47:36.370
of yours to work
saving yourself.

47:37.544 --> 47:38.890
- What do you think
I'm doing, son?

47:38.925 --> 47:42.411
- Honestly, I have no idea.

47:44.447 --> 47:45.724
I never have with you.

47:46.933 --> 47:50.868
I know I've already
lost one parent

47:50.902 --> 47:52.214
to this obsession of yours.

47:53.663 --> 47:56.045
I know I'm barely
coming to terms

47:56.080 --> 47:59.566
with what we are
facing right now.

47:59.600 --> 48:04.191
- All I'm facing is a
deadline to complete the work.

48:04.226 --> 48:05.158
Excuse the pun.

48:07.919 --> 48:09.472
- How can you joke?

48:09.507 --> 48:13.476
- Because what you see
as a frightening unknown,

48:14.684 --> 48:19.689
I see as an opportunity
for discovery,

48:20.932 --> 48:23.314
my last opportunity.

48:25.764 --> 48:27.111
I miss her, too,

48:30.873 --> 48:35.843
every day, but she, like me,

48:35.878 --> 48:38.501
lived for the discovery.

48:43.886 --> 48:46.509
- So neither one of you took
the time to consider me.

48:46.544 --> 48:48.822
- I was trying to save her!

48:48.856 --> 48:49.685
- Yeah?

48:51.100 --> 48:52.101
How'd that work out?

48:56.726 --> 48:58.936
Thank you for bringing him home.

48:58.970 --> 49:00.006
I have him from here.

49:04.217 --> 49:05.494
- Dr. Amberger.

49:14.986 --> 49:15.987
- Thank you, Jules.

49:18.231 --> 49:23.236
I'm very sorry, but I
think it's probably best

49:25.686 --> 49:29.414
if you go.

49:47.087 --> 49:49.607
- Wow, Nichols, you gotta
get a load of this one.

49:50.780 --> 49:52.092
Look at the size of that brute.

49:55.061 --> 49:56.890
- I was told someone was
looking for the sensory lab.

49:56.924 --> 49:57.856
- Yeah, that's us.

49:59.410 --> 50:01.136
[Jules sighs]

50:01.170 --> 50:02.516
- What gives?
- His son.

50:02.551 --> 50:04.346
Second person to
pull the plug today.

50:05.174 --> 50:06.762
He's putting Doc into a home.

50:11.077 --> 50:12.112
- So what's the plan?

50:15.081 --> 50:16.116
Are we gonna spring
him or something?

50:19.568 --> 50:20.396
What?

50:21.949 --> 50:23.882
I thought we were
all in for discovery.

50:25.091 --> 50:27.576
- No, I've never heard
of a Heinrich Kline.

50:27.610 --> 50:29.198
- Well, we have
reason to believe

50:29.233 --> 50:31.028
he may have been in contact
with one of your students,

50:31.062 --> 50:32.167
a Jules Christopher.

50:32.201 --> 50:34.238
- Of course.
- So you have heard of him.

50:35.756 --> 50:39.070
- Well, no, but...

50:51.393 --> 50:53.153
He may not be
going by that name.

50:57.951 --> 50:59.573
- Welcome to the last
place you're ever going

50:59.608 --> 51:01.092
to call home, most likely.

51:02.231 --> 51:04.647
- Well, I can certainly
smell the death.

51:06.132 --> 51:08.099
- Well, color me lucky
'cause I can't smell a thing.

51:08.134 --> 51:09.894
I think that's what keeps
my sunny disposition

51:09.928 --> 51:11.654
going all day long.

51:11.689 --> 51:13.000
- No sense of smell?

51:13.829 --> 51:15.106
Very interesting.

51:15.141 --> 51:18.937
- Well, let's just say I really
enjoyed [sniffs] the '80s.

51:21.630 --> 51:23.149
But I'm clean and sober now.

51:23.183 --> 51:25.254
Darned if the old sniffer
didn't give up on me, though.

51:25.289 --> 51:26.911
[pulsing electronic music]

51:26.945 --> 51:28.188
- He may have figured
out we were coming.

51:29.500 --> 51:32.261
Or we might not
be the only thing

51:32.296 --> 51:34.160
catching up with him.

51:34.194 --> 51:37.024
- I study something called
sensory enlightenment

51:37.956 --> 51:39.303
in individuals like you.

51:39.337 --> 51:41.443
- I'm gonna have to have you
hold that thought right now

51:41.477 --> 51:46.482
as I introduce you to
your [whistles] new abode.

51:47.311 --> 51:48.691
There's the dresser, closet.

51:49.520 --> 51:50.831
Restroom's through there.

51:50.866 --> 51:53.662
You can add to or
subtract furnishings

51:53.696 --> 51:56.285
and bring in some personal
bling, if you prefer.

51:56.320 --> 51:57.666
Important details.

51:57.700 --> 52:01.290
Breakfast is at 6:30,
lunch 11:00, dinner 4:45.

52:01.325 --> 52:03.327
We've got games, we've got TV,

52:03.361 --> 52:07.124
we've got exercise classes,
field trips to the zoo,

52:07.158 --> 52:08.539
local plays, things like that.

52:09.402 --> 52:10.955
Now I'm on the day shift,

52:10.989 --> 52:13.440
although there's talk of
moving me to the night shift.

52:13.475 --> 52:15.856
That's on account of
the head of scheduling,

52:15.891 --> 52:19.826
Joni, who used to
be my girlfriend,

52:19.860 --> 52:21.379
is now my ex-girlfriend,
and that's on account

52:21.414 --> 52:24.486
of Brenda, who's on
the day shift with me,

52:26.073 --> 52:28.628
and the night shift, if
you know what I mean.

52:28.662 --> 52:30.181
My name is Stevie.

52:30.216 --> 52:33.046
If you need anything from
me, just press that button.

52:33.080 --> 52:33.909
Any questions?

52:33.943 --> 52:35.082
- Peppermint?

52:35.117 --> 52:35.911
- [Stevie] Oh, I
don't mind if I do.

52:35.945 --> 52:36.774
- Any sign of him?

52:41.710 --> 52:42.538
- Nothing yet.

52:46.335 --> 52:47.336
- How's that taste?

52:47.371 --> 52:49.200
- Like peppermint I guess.

52:49.235 --> 52:50.167
- Very interesting.

52:51.375 --> 52:52.203
- It is?

52:53.722 --> 52:55.206
- Oh, there's his son.

52:55.241 --> 52:57.139
- I'll come to
you, where are you?

52:58.209 --> 53:01.592
[pulsing electronic music]

53:04.526 --> 53:06.113
Never mind, I'll
just find your phone.

53:07.460 --> 53:11.533
- Excuse me, son, would
you escort me to my room?

53:11.567 --> 53:12.775
- Sure.
- It's through the lobby

53:12.810 --> 53:13.707
and down the hall.

53:16.952 --> 53:18.333
- All right.

53:18.367 --> 53:19.748
We're all set up.

53:19.782 --> 53:22.199
We meet a specialist
in the morning.

53:22.233 --> 53:24.408
Dinner is in an hour.

53:26.375 --> 53:28.032
What do you wanna do?

53:28.066 --> 53:29.413
You wanna watch some
TV or something?

53:30.828 --> 53:32.381
- You should've
let me go with her.

53:32.416 --> 53:33.796
I had a plan.

53:35.142 --> 53:38.594
[pulsing electronic music]

53:43.634 --> 53:46.292
- Dad, this is the
best place for you now.

53:49.847 --> 53:51.297
- I know what's
happening to me, Noah.

53:51.331 --> 53:53.575
- Okay, okay.

53:53.609 --> 53:55.404
But can you just admit
that you can't battle

53:55.439 --> 53:57.303
this on your own?

53:57.337 --> 53:59.270
There's a team of doctors here,

53:59.305 --> 54:01.030
specialists that can help you.

54:04.793 --> 54:06.346
- I appreciate
what you're saying,

54:08.175 --> 54:10.005
but none of these
people can help me.

54:11.109 --> 54:12.559
Only I can help me.

54:12.594 --> 54:14.320
- You'll love my room.

54:14.354 --> 54:16.322
It's decorated in an homage

54:16.356 --> 54:20.395
to America's greatest
movie star, Burt Reynolds.

54:20.429 --> 54:22.328
What a dreamboat.
- I've gotta go.

54:25.020 --> 54:25.848
Sorry.

54:26.849 --> 54:28.299
- [Nichols] Agent Nichols, FBI.

54:28.334 --> 54:30.853
We need to speak with
a patient of yours.

54:30.888 --> 54:32.199
The name's Amberger.

54:32.234 --> 54:33.891
He should've checked
in earlier today.

54:35.789 --> 54:37.032
- You never understood.

54:41.208 --> 54:43.210
- You never took the
time to explain it.

54:47.318 --> 54:48.802
[phone buzzes]

54:48.837 --> 54:49.700
- Hello?

54:49.734 --> 54:51.253
- The FBI is in the building.

54:52.461 --> 54:53.773
I repeat, they are
in the building.

54:53.807 --> 54:54.636
- Who's there?

54:58.018 --> 54:59.123
- Hi.

54:59.157 --> 55:00.020
- You've gotta be kidding me.

55:00.055 --> 55:01.332
For God's sakes, do none of you

55:01.367 --> 55:03.472
get the seriousness of
what's happening here?

55:03.507 --> 55:04.473
- We have to go.

55:04.508 --> 55:06.337
- We are not going anywhere.

55:06.372 --> 55:08.788
My father is a sick man,
he needs to be here.

55:08.822 --> 55:11.653
- Doc, you don't
happen to be on the run

55:11.687 --> 55:14.311
from Johnny Law or something?

55:14.345 --> 55:15.484
- The FBI is coming.

55:15.519 --> 55:17.452
- Yeah, that,
apparently for you.

55:17.486 --> 55:18.384
- What, why?

55:19.350 --> 55:20.524
- You think this place is bad,

55:20.558 --> 55:21.559
you don't wanna
try federal prison.

55:21.594 --> 55:23.389
It's a real downer.

55:23.423 --> 55:24.390
- [Noah] Dad, what is this?

55:24.424 --> 55:25.391
- [Amberger] The past
catching up, son.

55:26.392 --> 55:27.841
- What did you do?

55:27.876 --> 55:29.878
- They wanted to
lock everything away,

55:29.912 --> 55:31.742
and I was trying to
save your mother.

55:33.709 --> 55:36.402
You're right, I never
explained it properly or fully,

55:36.436 --> 55:38.093
and I'm sorry for that.

55:38.127 --> 55:39.405
- I think this is a
conversation to have on the way.

55:39.439 --> 55:40.337
- The way?

55:40.371 --> 55:41.648
- [Jules] Out of here.

55:41.683 --> 55:43.478
- Are you sure they're
coming for my father?

55:43.512 --> 55:44.341
- Absolutely.

55:47.723 --> 55:48.828
- Thank you.

55:48.862 --> 55:50.726
[pulsing electronic music]

55:50.761 --> 55:52.245
- [Max] Let's go.

55:52.279 --> 55:54.385
- [Stevie] Whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa!

55:54.420 --> 55:55.352
Did you guys plan this?

55:55.386 --> 55:56.353
- What is happening, Dad?

55:56.387 --> 55:58.355
- The work is happening.

55:58.389 --> 55:59.390
Are you coming?

55:59.425 --> 56:00.736
- Me?
- Me?

56:00.771 --> 56:02.013
- Both of you.

56:02.048 --> 56:03.912
- If I come with
you and finish this,

56:03.946 --> 56:06.846
whatever it is, will you
come back here with me

56:06.880 --> 56:08.917
and face what you've done,

56:08.951 --> 56:11.540
face what is happening with you?

56:11.575 --> 56:14.060
- Whatever you want, son.

56:14.094 --> 56:15.406
- All right.

56:15.441 --> 56:16.442
- [Nichols] Where
else would residents

56:16.476 --> 56:17.719
normally be right now?

56:17.753 --> 56:19.376
- Well, dinner's not
for another 45 minutes,

56:19.410 --> 56:20.549
and it's free time right now,

56:20.584 --> 56:22.586
so anywhere, I guess.

56:24.588 --> 56:26.417
- We could really use that
nose of yours, Stevie.

56:26.452 --> 56:29.144
- What nose?
- Exactly.

56:29.178 --> 56:32.665
[pulsing electronic music]

56:35.771 --> 56:37.394
- Joni sure can hold a grudge.

56:38.429 --> 56:39.534
What the hell!

56:39.568 --> 56:43.020
[pulsing electronic music]

56:46.782 --> 56:49.406
Woo, yeah, turn on the
Dead, fire up a blunt,

56:49.440 --> 56:51.097
it'll be just like
the summer of '83.

56:51.131 --> 56:51.960
- Let's go.

56:52.788 --> 56:54.445
- Just one little stop.

56:54.480 --> 56:57.966
[pulsing electronic music]

57:06.353 --> 57:07.216
- I got the plate.

57:08.494 --> 57:09.356
- Great.

57:10.634 --> 57:13.119
Maybe this is a good
opportunity for us to regroup-

57:13.153 --> 57:15.086
- John, if you say the
word "fishing" right now,

57:15.121 --> 57:15.915
I am going to shoot you!

57:15.949 --> 57:16.743
- Fishing.

57:16.778 --> 57:17.606
- Hello?

57:18.987 --> 57:19.953
Anybody home?

57:46.566 --> 57:48.499
- What are you doing?

57:51.502 --> 57:52.848
- You're feeling the music?

57:54.056 --> 57:55.989
Well, that's what
my project does.

57:56.024 --> 57:57.957
Well, is supposed to do.

57:57.991 --> 57:59.752
It's supposed to
help you feel sound.

58:01.512 --> 58:02.340
- Yeah.

58:06.552 --> 58:08.554
[Jules sighs]

58:08.588 --> 58:11.660
I'm sorry, I know that
I've been distant,

58:11.695 --> 58:14.594
and I feel like I've made
an awful situation worse.

58:31.680 --> 58:34.856
- Well, of course,
if we get it to work.

58:37.548 --> 58:42.519
Actually, I think that
you just solved it.

58:44.693 --> 58:48.145
- Would you be wiling to
help me with something?

58:49.042 --> 58:50.527
- Are you up for a road trip?

58:52.080 --> 58:53.702
- We got him.
- Yeah?

58:53.737 --> 58:56.567
- Well, we know where
they're going anyways.

58:56.602 --> 58:58.742
We think they're headed
to a town called McCall.

59:09.269 --> 59:10.477
- All right, when
do we head out?

59:10.512 --> 59:12.134
- I sent out an APB
with the local sheriff.

59:12.169 --> 59:13.722
We'll head out tomorrow.

59:13.757 --> 59:15.655
- Well, in that case, you
need a drinking buddy?

59:16.656 --> 59:17.726
- I drink alone.

59:23.663 --> 59:24.837
- I drink alone.

59:26.424 --> 59:31.326
[waves crash]
[soft music]

59:52.623 --> 59:53.659
- [Amberger] Place
has hardly changed.

59:53.693 --> 59:54.798
- If it ain't broke.

59:56.213 --> 59:58.905
Gotta say, never thought
you'd set foot in here again.

59:58.940 --> 1:00:00.113
You dying or something?

1:00:00.148 --> 1:00:01.736
- Aren't we all?

1:00:01.770 --> 1:00:02.633
- Who's the girlfriend?

1:00:02.668 --> 1:00:04.635
Seems a little young for you.

1:00:04.670 --> 1:00:07.086
- Jules, and how?

1:00:07.120 --> 1:00:08.743
- The way the air moves
around you when you walk,

1:00:08.777 --> 1:00:11.366
and you don't smell
old like this one.

1:00:12.194 --> 1:00:14.611
- She's a colleague.

1:00:14.645 --> 1:00:18.028
Jules, meet Toby, one
of the original Five.

1:00:18.856 --> 1:00:20.409
- So, that's why you're here.

1:00:21.687 --> 1:00:24.828
- It's time, it's time
we finished the work.

1:00:26.036 --> 1:00:27.796
Is it all still here?

1:00:27.831 --> 1:00:29.522
- It's here.

1:00:29.556 --> 1:00:30.937
Not sure if it's of
much use anymore.

1:00:30.972 --> 1:00:33.146
Didn't go so well last time.

1:00:33.181 --> 1:00:34.700
- We didn't have
all the pieces then.

1:00:34.734 --> 1:00:36.563
- So that's what you've got
waiting in that old bus.

1:00:36.598 --> 1:00:38.358
- Seriously, how are you-

1:00:38.393 --> 1:00:40.119
- I'm assuming that you
discussed the notion

1:00:40.153 --> 1:00:41.879
of sensory enlightenment,
being that you

1:00:41.914 --> 1:00:43.640
just trekked all
the way out here.

1:00:43.674 --> 1:00:45.745
- It's just so amazing.

1:00:46.712 --> 1:00:48.575
- Well, anyone can
get good at anything,

1:00:48.610 --> 1:00:50.025
given enough time or practice.

1:00:51.199 --> 1:00:52.027
Let's have a look.

1:00:53.719 --> 1:00:54.996
- You think they're
gonna let us in soon?

1:00:55.030 --> 1:00:55.859
I'm starving.

1:00:57.550 --> 1:01:02.520
- I think that's his mom.

1:01:37.452 --> 1:01:42.457
- You know, you cut
something out of your life,

1:01:43.630 --> 1:01:47.565
you think it's
gone, that's done,

1:01:50.776 --> 1:01:52.743
but then you see it again,

1:01:54.296 --> 1:01:57.817
and then you realize
it was always there

1:01:59.508 --> 1:02:00.820
just under the surface,

1:02:07.344 --> 1:02:08.172
waiting for you.

1:02:21.807 --> 1:02:22.946
- How do we turn it all on?

1:02:39.790 --> 1:02:43.104
[machinery hums]

1:02:43.138 --> 1:02:44.139
What happened?

1:02:44.174 --> 1:02:46.107
- Power surge, I'm guessing.

1:02:46.141 --> 1:02:48.799
There's a breaker
box in the corner.

1:02:48.834 --> 1:02:50.732
